INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '22fb4cde-82f7-4c9d-90fc-d180d18a9ca8',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Scala Dev Tooling — REPL, Debugger, and LSP in Your Daily Workflow$escape$,
  $escape$The Scala REPL (`scala` or `sbt console`) is more than a scratchpad — with `:paste` mode you can drop in multi-line class definitions, and `:type` / `:kind` give you type-level introspection without compiling a full project. Ammonite (`amm`) upgrades this further: magic imports like `import $ivy.'org.typelevel::cats-core:2.10.0'` pull dependencies on the fly, and scripts are first-class.

For debugging, the JVM gives you full JDWP support. In sbt, `set fork := true` combined with `javaOptions += "-agentlib:jdwp=transport=dt_socket,server=y,suspend=n,address=5005"` exposes a debug port that IntelliJ or VS Code attaches to natively.

LSP support is handled by Metals, the de facto language server. It integrates with sbt, Mill, and Bloop via BSP. Key wins: inline type hints via `textDocument/hover`, worksheet mode (`.worksheet.sc` files evaluated inline like a REPL), and semantic highlighting. Pair Metals with Bloop for sub-second incremental compilation — `bloop compile <project>` bypasses sbt's shell overhead entirely for tighter feedback loops.$escape$,
  $escape$// sbt build.sbt — wire up remote debugging + Bloop export
lazy val root = project.in(file("."))
  .settings(
    scalaVersion := "3.4.1",
    fork := true,
    javaOptions ++= Seq(
      "-agentlib:jdwp=transport=dt_socket,server=y,suspend=n,address=5005"
    )
  )

// Then in shell:
// sbt bloopInstall          <- generates .bloop/ config
// bloop compile root        <- fast incremental compile
// bloop console root        <- REPL with full classpath$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
