INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '5df1ab9a-c33a-4161-8179-2c191a1be013',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Scala Horizontal Scaling — Actor Systems and Thread Model Implications$escape$,
  $escape$Scala's horizontal scaling story is inseparable from its concurrency model. Akka's actor system uses a fixed fork-join thread pool (`akka.actor.default-dispatcher`) shared across all actors — by default sized to available CPU cores. This means a single blocking call inside an actor (e.g., a synchronous JDBC query) starves the dispatcher, causing cascading mailbox backlogs across the entire node.

For horizontal scaling, this matters because your throughput ceiling is not network or CPU — it's dispatcher saturation. The fix is isolation: route blocking operations to a dedicated dispatcher via `context.system.dispatchers.lookup("blocking-io-dispatcher")`, configured with a thread-pool-executor rather than fork-join.

With Akka Cluster, actors gain location transparency via `ActorSelection` and `ClusterSharding`. Sharding distributes entity actors across nodes deterministically by key hash, enabling stateful horizontal scaling without a shared-state bottleneck. Combined with `BackpressureStrategy` in Akka Streams, you get end-to-end flow control across a cluster — critical when scaling out consumer nodes faster than producers.$escape$,
  $escape$// application.conf — isolate blocking I/O from actor dispatcher
blocking-io-dispatcher {
  type = Dispatcher
  executor = "thread-pool-executor"
  thread-pool-executor {
    fixed-pool-size = 32
  }
  throughput = 1
}

// Inside an actor — offload blocking work
val blockingDispatcher = context.system.dispatchers.lookup("blocking-io-dispatcher")
Future {
  // JDBC / blocking HTTP call here
  database.query("SELECT ...")
}(blockingDispatcher).pipeTo(self)$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
